spective on Canada’s planning history provides an important counter-narrative to the “official” story of the profession. It challenges us to re-evaluate not only the profession’s past, but also its role in creating a more inclusive and equitable future.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCity planningzCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aCity planning--Canada--History--20th century. 0aWomen city plannerszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 7aARCHITECTURE / Urban & Land Use Planning.2bisacsh1 aMarkovich, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311141793640uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077482589440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774825894423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774825894/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-141793-6  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles